#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/metrics.md
M|references|Metrics are the language of validated learning. The wrong metrics create the illusion of progress while the startup drifts toward failure. The right metrics force honest conversations and drive real d
M|references|Vanity metrics make you feel good but do not inform decisions. They go up and to the right even when the product is failing.
M|references|**Common vanity metrics:**
M|references|- Total registered users (includes dead accounts)
M|references|- Total page views (says nothing about engagement quality)
M|references|- Total downloads (says nothing about retention)
M|references|- Total revenue without ctx (growing because of more users, not better product)
M|references|- soc media followers (does not correlate with business outcomes)
M|references|- Press mentions (feels good, rarely converts)
M|references|**Why they are dangerous:** Vanity metrics can be manipulated, misinterpreted, and used to justify continuing a failing str. A startup with 100,000 registered users and 500 active users is failing, bu
M|references|Actionable metrics directly inform decisions. If the metric changes, you change your behavior.
M|references|**Properties of actionable metrics:**
M|references|- Tied to a specific, repeatable action
M|references|- Measured per cohort, not in aggregate
M|references|- Have a clear cause-and-effect relationship with product changes
M|references|- Can be independently verified
M|references|**Examples of actionable metrics:**
M|references|| Vanity Version | Actionable Version | Why It Is Better |
M|references||---------------|-------------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Total users | Weekly new signups by acquisition channel | Shows which channels work and whether growth is accelerating |
M|references|| Total revenue | Revenue per user by cohort | Shows whether product improvements increase monetization |
M|references|| Page views | Pages per ses by user segment | Shows engagement depth and cnt effectiveness |
M|references|| App downloads | Day-7 retention rate by cohort | Shows whether users find lasting value |
M|references|| Email subscribers | Email open rate by cg type | Shows cnt relevance and audience engagement |
M|references|Every metric you track should pass the Three A's test:
M|references|A metric is actionable if it demonstrates clear cause and effect. When you make a product change and the metric moves, you can attribute the change to your action.
M|references|**Test:** "If this metric drops by 20%, do I know what to do?" If the answer is no, the metric is not actionable.
M|references|**Example:** Onboarding completion rate is actionable. If it drops, you investigate and fix the onboarding flow. Total signups is less actionable because it depends on mkt spend, seasonality, and pres
M|references|A metric is accessible if the entire team can understand it and access it easily.
M|references|**Test:** "Can every team member explain what this metric means and find the current value in under 60 seconds?"
M|references|**Implementation:**
M|references|- Use simple, human-readable dashboards
M|references|- Display metrics on a shared screen or Slack channel
M|references|- Define every metric in a shared glossary
M|references|- Avoid jargon and complex calculations in primary dashboards
M|references|- Report metrics in absolute numbers alongside percentages (percentages without ctx mislead)
M|references|A metric is auditable if the data can be verified and traced to individual customer behavior.
M|references|**Test:** "Can I look at the underlying data and verify this number is correct? Can I talk to real customers whose behavior contributed to this metric?"
M|references|**Implementation:**
M|references|- Ensure data pipelines are transparent and well-documented
M|references|- Maintain the ability to drill down from aggregate metrics to individual events
M|references|- Cross-check automated reports against manual spot checks periodically
M|references|- Keep raw event data accessible (do not only store aggregates)
M|references|A cohort groups users by a shared experience within a defined time window.
M|references|**Common cohort definitions:**
M|references|- **Acquisition cohort:** Users who signed up in the same week/month
M|references|- **Behavioral cohort:** Users who completed a specific action (e.g., made first purchase)
M|references|- **Channel cohort:** Users acquired through the same mkt channel
M|references|Select the metric that best reflects the hypothesis you are testing.
M|references|| Goal | Metric | Measurement |
M|references||------|--------|-------------|
M|references|| Product stickiness | Retention rate | % of users active in period N who return in period N+1 |
M|references|| Monetization | Revenue per user | Total cohort revenue divided by cohort size |
M|references|| Engagement | Core actions per user | Average number of key actions per active user per period |
M|references|| Growth | Referral rate | Number of invites sent that convert, per cohort member |
M|references|**Retention cohort table example:**
M|references|| Signup Week | Size | Week 1 | Week 2 | Week 3 | Week 4 | Week 8 | Week 12 |
M|references||------------|------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|---------|
M|references|| Jan 1-7 | 200 | 42% | 28% | 22% | 18% | 12% | 9% |
M|references|| Jan 8-14 | 180 | 45% | 31% | 25% | 20% | 14% | 11% |
M|references|| Jan 15-21 | 220 | 48% | 35% | 28% | 23% | 16% | - |
M|references|| Jan 22-28 | 250 | 50% | 37% | 30% | 25% | - | - |
M|references|| Feb 1-7 | 230 | 53% | 39% | 32% | - | - | - |
M|references|**Read across rows:** How does a single cohort degrade over time? This is the retention curve. Steeper = worse retention.
M|references|**Read down columns:** How do newer cohorts compare to older ones at the same age? Improving = product is getting better. Declining = product is getting worse.
M|references|**The key insight:** If newer cohorts retain better at the same age, your product improvements are working. If they retain worse, something is going wrong despite growth.
M|references|| Pattern | What It Means | Action |
M|references||---------|--------------|--------|
M|references|| Newer cohorts retain better | Product improvements are working | Continue current str; double down on winning changes |
M|references|| Newer cohorts retain worse | Product or acquisition quality is declining | Investigate recent changes; audit acquisition channels |
M|references|| Retention flattens at a certain week | Product has a natural engagement ceiling | Focus on deepening value for retained users |
M|references|| Retention drops sharply in Week 1 | Onboarding or first-use experience is broken | Redesign activation flow |
M|references|| Later cohorts are larger but retain worse | Growth is outpacing product quality | Slow growth; fix retention before scaling |
M|references|Dave McClure's Pirate Metrics framework maps cleanly to lean startup stages:
M|references|**Question:** How do users find you?
M|references|| Metric | Formula | Good Benchmark |
M|references||--------|---------|----------------|
M|references|| Visitor-to-signup rate | Signups / Unique visitors | 2-5% for B2C, 5-15% for B2B |
M|references|| Cost per acquisition (CPA) | mkt spend / New signups | Varies by industry; must be below LTV |
M|references|| Channel mix | % of signups by source | No single channel > 50% (diversification) |
M|references|**Question:** Do users have a great first experience?
M|references|| Metric | Formula | Good Benchmark |
M|references||--------|---------|----------------|
M|references|| Onboarding completion rate | Users completing setup / Signups | 60-80% |
M|references|| Time to first value | Time from signup to core action | Under 5 minutes for consumer; under 1 day for B2B |
M|references|| Aha moment conversion | Users reaching key milestone / Signups | 40-70% |
M|references|**Question:** Do users come back?
M|references|| Metric | Formula | Good Benchmark |
M|references||--------|---------|----------------|
M|references|| Day 1 / Day 7 / Day 30 retention | Active on Day N / Cohort size | Varies by category (see below) |
M|references|| Weekly active / Monthly active ratio | WAU / MAU | 25%+ is healthy |
M|references|| Churn rate | Users lost / Total users per period | Under 5% monthly for SaaS |
M|references|**Retention benchmarks by category:**
M|references|| Category | Day 1 | Day 7 | Day 30 |
M|references||----------|-------|-------|--------|
M|references|| soc/messaging | 50-70% | 30-50% | 20-35% |
M|references|| E-commerce | 25-40% | 10-20% | 5-15% |
M|references|| SaaS (B2B) | 80-95% | 70-85% | 60-80% |
M|references|| Mobile gaming | 35-50% | 15-25% | 5-15% |
M|references|| Productivity tools | 40-60% | 25-40% | 15-30% |
M|references|**Question:** How do you make money?
M|references|| Metric | Formula | Good Benchmark |
M|references||--------|---------|----------------|
M|references|| Average revenue per user (ARPU) | Total revenue / Active users | Depends on pricing model |
M|references|| Lifetime value (LTV) | ARPU multiplied by average lifespan | 3x+ CAC |
M|references|| Conversion to paid | Paid users / Total active users | 2-5% freemium; 15-30% free trial |
M|references|| Net revenue retention | (Starting MRR + expansion - contraction - churn) / Starting MRR | 100%+ for B2B SaaS |
M|references|**Question:** Do users tell others?
M|references|| Metric | Formula | Good Benchmark |
M|references||--------|---------|----------------|
M|references|| Viral coefficient (K) | Invites per user multiplied by conversion rate of invites | Above 0.5 is strong; above 1.0 is viral |
M|references|| Net Promoter Score (NPS) | % Promoters minus % Detractors | 40+ is excellent |
M|references|| Referral rate | Users who refer / Total active users | 10%+ indicates strong word of mouth |
M|references|| Organic traffic share | Organic visits / Total visits | 40%+ suggests brand strength |
M|references|Focus on engagement and retention. Revenue metrics are premature.
M|references|**Primary metrics:**
M|references|- Retention (Week 1, Week 4 by cohort)
M|references|- Core action completion rate
M|references|- Qualitative: Sean Ellis test ("How would you feel if you could no longer use this product?")
M|references|- NPS from active users
M|references|- ses frequency
M|references|**Do not optimize:** CAC, LTV, revenue, viral coefficient. These are meaningless without product-market fit.
M|references|Focus on unit economics and channel efficiency.
M|references|**Primary metrics:**
M|references|- LTV and LTV/CAC ratio
M|references|- CAC by channel
M|references|- Monthly retention and churn by cohort
M|references|- Revenue per user trends
M|references|- Activation rate
M|references|**Do not optimize:** Brand awareness, market share, total revenue. Scale metrics come after unit economics are healthy.
M|references|Focus on efficiency at scale and sustainable growth.
M|references|**Primary metrics:**
M|references|- Net revenue retention
M|references|- Payback period (months to recover CAC)
M|references|- Gross margin
M|references|- Growth rate (month over month)
M|references|- Channel saturation indicators
M|references|Each dashboard should answer one question. Do not combine acquisition, engagement, and revenue on a single screen. Create separate views for separate questions.
M|references|A single number is meaningless without ctx. Always show the metric over time (at least 8 weeks) and compare to the previous period.
M|references|Default views should show cohort data. Aggregate views should require a deliberate click or toggle. This prevents the team from accidentally reading vanity numbers.
M|references|Percentages without absolute numbers mislead. "50% conversion rate" sounds great until you learn the sample was 4 users. Always show both the percentage and the underlying count.
M|references|Add annotations to the dashboard showing when experiments launched. This creates a visual connection between actions and results.
M|references|| Mistake | Why It Is Wrong | Correction |
M|references||---------|----------------|------------|
M|references|| Tracking 30+ metrics simultaneously | Attention is diluted; team cannot focus | Pick 3-5 primary metrics per stage |
M|references|| Celebrating total user growth while retention declines | Growth masks product problems | Always lead with cohort retention |
M|references|| Measuring weekly without cohort segmentation | Cannot distinguish product improvement from mkt spend | Segment every metric by cohort |
M|references|| Setting metric targets after seeing results | Confirmation bias; any result looks like success | Set targets before running experiments |
M|references|| Ignoring qualitative data because "we have the numbers" | Numbers tell you what; interviews tell you why | Pair every quantitative metric with 5-10 customer conversations per month |
M|references|| Optimizing a metric that does not connect to business outcomes | Local optimization without global impact | Map every metric to a business outcome (retention to LTV, activation to retention, etc.) |
M|references|| Changing metric definitions mid-experiment | Results become incomparable | Lock definitions before experiments start; create new metrics if needed |
M|references|Good metrics create honest conversations. Bad metrics create comfortable delusions. The discipline of innovation accounting is choosing honesty over comfort.